ce:section.ce:para:
Amino-N-GQDs were prepared through the ultrasonic shearing of graphene oxide sheets executed using a modified Hummers method [9]. According to transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images (Figs. S1a–S1b and Table S1), the estimated mean lateral size of the derived amino-N-GQDs was 9.3 ± 0.9 nm. Fig. S1 presents the results obtained from other relevant characterization processes, which confirmed that the amino-N-GQDs had been successfully prepared. However, as mentioned, the as-prepared amino-N-GQDs exhibited EWD-PL, which could be attributed to quantum size effects, zigzag edge sites, and surface defect states [2–4]. The prepared amino-N-GQDs were subjected to a size-based sorting process; specifically, they were sorted using sieves with pore sizes of 1, 50, and 300 kD. According to high-resolution TEM images (Fig. 1
                        ; low-magnification TEM images are presented in Fig. S2), the sorted amino-N-GQDs had mean lateral pore sizes of 0.8 ± 0.1 nm (hereafter referred to as amino-N-GQD0.8), 6.4 ± 0.2 nm (hereafter referred to as amino-N-GQD6.4), and 10.1 ± 0.2 nm (hereafter referred to as amino-N-GQD10.1), which were consistent with the Raman spectroscopy results (Fig. S3). Atomic force microscopy was used to determine the height profile of the materials, and the micrographs revealed that a single layer of the sorted materials had a thickness range of 1.16 ± 0.04 to 1.21 ± 0.05 nm (Fig. S4). Furthermore, X-ray diffraction was performed to analyze the crystallinity of the materials (Fig. S5). The surface chemistry of the sorted amino-N-GQDs was investigated through X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy, and the results revealed O/C and N/C atomic ratios of 0.33–0.42 and 0.048–0.054, respectively, indicating surface oxidation (Figs. S6–S7). When the particle size of the sorted materials was increased, favorable C–N, pyridine–N, amino–N, pyrrolic–N, and amide–N were observed. The concentration of N functionalities increased with particle size, and oxidization interaction mainly occurred in six-membered and five-membered aromatic heterocycles. When the particle size of the sorted materials was decreased, the concentrations of C–C/CC, C–O, CO, and quaternary–N functionalities increased, probably because of the increase in edge-site contributions. This finding suggests that the number of O-based and N-based groups influenced the O and N content. UV–visible (UV–vis) spectrometry revealed the maximal and edge absorbance peaks of the sorted amino-N-GQDs. These absorbance peaks were attributed to the π–π∗ transition of aromatic CC bonds (sp2 domains), and the corresponding wavelengths of the normalized maximal absorbance were approximately 216, 369, and 588 nm for amino-N-GQD0.8, amino-N-GQD6.4, and amino-N-GQD10.1, respectively. Peaks attributed to the n–π∗ transition of the CO shoulder and C–N were also observed, and the corresponding wavelengths of the edge absorbance were approximately 320, 480, and 635 for amino-N-GQD0.8, amino-N-GQD6.4, and amino-N-GQD10.1, respectively. These peaks were related to the π electron transition in the O-containing and N-containing GQDs (Fig. S8). Furthermore, the sorted amino-N-GQDs with PL emissions in the UV–NIR light region had PL peaks at approximately 374 nm (amino-N-GQD0.8), 561 nm (amino-N-GQD6.4), and 773 nm (amino-N-GQD10.1; insets in Fig. 1; Fig. S9). Deconvoluting the normalized PL excitation spectra revealed three absorptive transition peaks, namely a long-wavelength peak that was ascribed to the n → π∗ transition, an intermediate-wavelength peak that was ascribed to the π → π∗ transition, and a short-wavelength peak that was ascribed to the n → σ∗ transition (Fig. S10). In addition, UV photoelectron spectroscopy revealed n-state levels that were located at nearly the same energy position (6.4–6.5 eV) regardless of particle size, demonstrating that the sorted amino-N-GQDs had reached the highest occupied orbital level (Fig. S11). Accordingly, the quantum confinement of particle size regulated the wavelengths of the radiative transitions; the sorted amino-N-GQDs also exhibited EWI-PL emissions, implying insufficient trap states between the π∗ and n-state energy levels. The level of the n states was unaffected by particle size, whereas the levels of the π, π∗, and σ∗ orbitals varied considerably with particle size. The EWI-PL of the sorted amino-N-GQDs was attributed to the π∗ → n recombination, which involves phonon scattering and an electron transition. The relaxation of electrons from the σ∗ orbital to the π∗ orbital was determined to be essential for PL emissions induced by short-wavelength excitation. On the basis of the aforementioned results, a schematic of the energy levels of the sorted amino-N-GQDs was derived, as illustrated in Fig. S12. The absolute fluorescence QY levels [10] of amino-N-GQD0.8, amino-N-GQD6.4, and amino-N-GQD10.1 were approximately 0.21, 0.33, and 0.40, respectively (Table 1
                        ), which are higher than those documented in other studies (Table S2). These results indicate the successful preparation of sorted amino-N-GQDs with EWI-PL.
